<DocsLayout
  title="godex harness"
  eyebrow="Architecture"
  description="The shape of the godex core: runner, providers, tools, and bus."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/install/", title: "Install & run" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/extensibility/", title: "Extensibility" }}
>
  <p>
    <code>godex</code> is the engine inside <code>gode</code>. The CLI, the TUI, the ACP
    transport, and the app server are all thin shells over it. If you understand how godex
    is laid out, you understand how the agent runs.
  </p>

  <h2>The pieces</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Runner</strong> — drives a turn end to end: ingest user input, call the provider, dispatch tool calls, fan out events.</li>
    <li><strong>Provider interface</strong> — abstracts the model. Adapters for OpenAI/Codex, Anthropic Claude (in progress), and a deterministic mock for tests.</li>
    <li><strong>Tool registry</strong> — a uniform interface for built-in tools and MCP-exposed tools.</li>
    <li><strong>MCP manager</strong> — owns the lifecycle of attached MCP servers and surfaces their tools into the registry.</li>
    <li><strong>Event bus</strong> — typed events for every state transition. Multiple subscribers, no coupling.</li>
    <li><strong>JSONL journal</strong> — durable per-session log of events. Replay, debugging, and resume all read from it.</li>
    <li><strong>Workspace state</strong> — the agent's view of the working directory: files, todos, goal state, memory.</li>
    <li><strong>Context management</strong> — keeps token budgets sane across long sessions, including compaction.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How a turn flows</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>The transport (TUI, ACP, app-server) calls <code>session/prompt</code> on the runner.</li>
    <li>The runner emits a <code>turn_started</code> event and asks the provider for the next assistant turn.</li>
    <li>Provider streams back text deltas and tool calls. Each delta becomes an event.</li>
    <li>Each tool call goes through the registry. If it requires permission, the runner emits a permission request event and waits.</li>
    <li>Tool results are appended to the conversation; the loop continues until the provider signals end of turn.</li>
    <li>Every event is journaled to JSONL alongside being broadcast on the bus.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Why this shape.</strong> Putting every transition on a typed bus means
    transports, observers, and replay tools never need to call into runner internals. They
    just subscribe.
  </div>

  <h2>Why Go</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>One static binary, fast cold start, easy to ship.</li>
    <li>Goroutines and channels map naturally onto event-driven concurrency.</li>
    <li>Strong stdlib for processes, IO, and JSON-RPC transports — exactly what an agent harness needs.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
